\section{The strange case of the Riemann sphere}
In this final section, we explore in detail all the theory developed in the case of the bounded derived category of coherent sheaves on the complex projective line (i.e. the Riemann sphere) $\mathbb{P}^1_{\mathbb{C}}$, which is simply the topological bidimensional sphere with the unique complex structure it carries (SEE PICTURE ABOVE). This will be our only, big, example. \\
Recall that a coherent sheaf on a curve $C$ is a direct sum of a vector bundle and a torsion sheaf (this is essentially the structure theorem for finitely generated modules over principal ideal domains) and that torsion sheaves (which are direct sums of sheaves supported in a point) are of finite length, and thus posses a Jordan-Holder filtration with simple quotients. Moreover, the simple objects in the abelian category of coherent sheaves $\textnormal{Coh}(C)$ are the skyscraper sheaves of (closed) points, which we denote $\mathcal{O}_x$, with $x \in C$. This implies that $\textnormal{Coh}(C)$, besides being Noetherian, is not Artinian, since only sheaves with finite support can have Jordan-Holder filtrations. \\
Now, the Picard group $\textnormal{Pic}(\mathbb{P}^1_{\mathbb{C}})$ is isomorphic to $\mathbb{Z}$, with isomorphism given by the first Chern class. This means that there is a unique line bundle, denoted $\mathcal{O}_{\mathbb{P}^1_{\mathbb{C}}}(n)$, for each $n \in \mathbb{Z}$, and among them the canonical bundle (which is the cotangent one) is $\omega_{\mathbb{P}^1_{\mathbb{C}}}=\mathcal{O}_{\mathbb{P}^1_{\mathbb{C}}}(-2)$. Moreover, the beautiful Birkhoff-Grothendieck theorem tells us that each vector bundle on the Riemann sphere is direct sum of line bundles (in an essentially unique way). \\
From now on, denote $\mathscr{D}=\mathscr{D}^{\textnormal{b}}(\textnormal{Coh}(\mathbb{P}^1_{\mathbb{C}}))$. By the classical vanishing theorems for sheaf cohomology, $\mathscr{D}$ is Hom-finite with homological dimension $1$ with respect to $\textnormal{Coh}(\mathbb{P}^1_{\mathbb{C}})$. Moreover, there is an isomorphism of groups $$\textnormal{Aut}(\mathscr{D})=\mathbb{Z}^2 \rtimes \textnormal{PGL}_2(\mathbb{C})$$ 
where a copy of $\mathbb{Z}=\textnormal{Pic}(\mathbb{P}^1_{\mathbb{C}})$ is identified with twists by line bundles, the other by translations, and the projective linear group is simply the group of automoprhisms of the Riemann sphere as a complex manifold. FORSE METTI IL GRUPPO DI GROTHENDIECK. \\

\begin{prop}
Fix a total order on $\mathbb{P}^1_{\mathbb{C}}$ and set $\widetilde{J}=\mathbb{Z} \times ( \mathbb{Z} \sqcup \mathbb{P}^1_{\mathbb{C}})$, where the product is lexicographical, the coproduct is given by setting $\mathbb{P}^1_{\mathbb{C}} > \mathbb{Z}$ and $\mathbb{Z}$ acts on the left factor. For $i,j \in \mathbb{Z}$, $x \in \mathbb{P}^1_{\mathbb{C}}$ set $$\mathscr{P}_{(i,x)}=\langle \mathcal{O}_x[i] \rangle $$ $$\mathscr{P}_{(i,j)}=\langle \mathcal{O}_{\mathbb{P}^1_{\mathbb{C}}}(j)[i] \rangle $$
Then $\mathscr{P}$ is a $\widetilde{J}$-slicing on $\mathscr{D}$. 
\end{prop}

\begin{proof}
First of all, by above discussion $\textnormal{Coh}(\mathbb{P}^1_{\mathbb{C}})$ is the extension-closed subcategory of $\mathscr{D}$ generated by line bundles and skyscraper sheaves of points. Thus, by Proposition ???, is suffices to show that $\mathscr{P}_x=\langle \mathcal{O}_x \rangle$, $\mathscr{P}_j=\langle \mathcal{O}_{\mathbb{P}^1_{\mathbb{C}}}(j) \rangle$ with $j \in \mathbb{Z}$ and  $x \in \mathbb{P}^1_{\mathbb{C}}$ defines $(\mathbb{Z} \sqcup \mathbb{P}^1_{\mathbb{C}})$-stability data on $\textnormal{Coh}(\mathbb{P}^1_{\mathbb{C}})$. As usual, the nontrivial part is the construction of Harder-Narasimhan filtrations. But this is easy because each coherent sheaf is sum of a torsion one and line bundles, and thus it suffices to construct the filtrations for torsion sheaves. These can be taken as particular Jordan-Holder filtrations, so that the points whose skyscrapers appear as simple quotients are ordered decreasingly with respect to the order on $\mathbb{P}^1_{\mathbb{C}}$. 
\end{proof}

Beware that $\widetilde{J}$ depends on a total order on $\mathbb{P}^1_{\mathbb{C}}$. 

\begin{prop}
For $n \in \mathbb{Z}$ and  $P \subseteq \mathbb{P}^1_{\mathbb{C}}$, the following are hearts of $\mathscr{D}$: $$\heartsuit_P = \langle \{ \mathcal{O}_x \}_{x \in P} \cup  \{ \mathcal{O}_x [1] \}_{x \in \mathbb{P}^1_{\mathbb{C}} \setminus P} \cup \textnormal{Pic}(\mathbb{P}^1_{\mathbb{C}})[1] \rangle $$ 
$$\heartsuit_n= \langle \{ \mathcal{O}_x  \}_{x \in \mathbb{P}^1_{\mathbb{C}}} \cup \{ \mathcal{O}_{\mathbb{P}^1_{\mathbb{C}}}(j) \}_{j>n} \cup  \{ \mathcal{O}_{\mathbb{P}^1_{\mathbb{C}}}(j) [1] \}_{j \le n} \rangle$$
\end{prop}

\begin{proof}
First of all, choose an order on $\mathbb{P}^1_{\mathbb{C}}$ so that $P$ is an upper set (this is clearly always possible). Then the following are intervals in $\widetilde{J}$ which are systems of representative for the action of $\mathbb{Z}$:  $$( \{ 0 \} \times P ) \cup ( \{ 1 \} \times (\mathbb{P}^1_{\mathbb{C}} \setminus P \sqcup \mathbb{Z}))$$ $$ ( \{ 0 \} \times ( \mathbb{P}^1_{\mathbb{C}} \sqcup \mathbb{Z}_{>n} )) \cup ( \{1 \} \times \mathbb{Z}_{\le n} )$$
We conclude applying Proposition ??? to $\mathscr{P}$. 
\end{proof}

Observe that $\heartsuit_n$ is obtained from $\heartsuit_0$ by twisting by $\mathcal{O}_{\mathbb{P}^1_{\mathbb{C}}}(n)$. Moreover, if $P'=F(P)$ for some $F \in \textnormal{PGL}_2(\mathbb{C})$, then $\heartsuit_{P'}$ is obtained from $\heartsuit_P$ by acting by $F$. \\
