%Moreover, since a morphism of $\mathbb{Z}$-posets $2\mathbb{Z} \longrightarrow \mathbb{Z}$ is determined by first choosing freely where to send $0$, and then deciding if sending $1$ to $0$ or to $1$, we have an isomorphism of $\mathbb{Z}$-posets: $$\textnormal{Hom}_{\textnormal{Pos}_{\mathbb{Z}}}(J_p,\mathbb{Z})=\mathbb{Z} \times \{0,1 \}$$ 
