\begin{prop}
Pick $k \in \mathbb{Z}$,  $p \in \mathbb{Z}_{\ge 1}$. For $i \in \mathbb{Z}$ set $$\mathscr{P}^{k,p}_{(i,0)}=\langle \mathcal{O}_{\mathbb{P}^1_{\mathbb{C}}}(k)[p+i]\rangle$$ $$\mathscr{P}^{k,p}_{(i,1)}=\langle \mathcal{O}_{\mathbb{P}^1_{\mathbb{C}}}(k+1)[i]\rangle$$ 
Then $\mathscr{P}^{k,p}$ is a $\mathbb{Z} \times \{ 0, 1 \}$-slicing on $\mathscr{D}$.  
\end{prop}

\begin{proof}
Since $\mathscr{D}$ has homological dimension $1$ with respect to $\textnormal{Coh}(\mathbb{P}^1_{\mathbb{C}})$, by Proposition ??? each object of $\mathscr{D}$ is a finite direct sum of shifts of coherent sheaves, which are by the other hand finite sums of torsion sheaves supported in a point and line bundles. Thus, it suffices to construct Postnikov towers for the latters ones. But if $ \mathcal{O}_{\mathbb{P}^1_{\mathbb{C}}}(n)$ is a line bundle with $n > k+1$, we have a short exact sequence in $\textnormal{Coh}( \mathbb{P}^1_{\mathbb{C}})$:  $$0 \longrightarrow  \mathcal{O}_{\mathbb{P}^1_{\mathbb{C}}}(k)^{\oplus (n-k-1)} \longrightarrow  \mathcal{O}_{\mathbb{P}^1_{\mathbb{C}}}(k+1)^{\oplus(n-k)} \longrightarrow  \mathcal{O}_{\mathbb{P}^1_{\mathbb{C}}}(n) \longrightarrow 0$$ 
Rotating the induced distinguished triangle, we get: $$ \mathcal{O}_{\mathbb{P}^1_{\mathbb{C}}}(k+1)^{\oplus(n-k)} \longrightarrow  \mathcal{O}_{\mathbb{P}^1_{\mathbb{C}}}(n) \longrightarrow \mathcal{O}_{\mathbb{P}^1_{\mathbb{C}}}(k)[1]^{\oplus (n-k-1)} \longrightarrow $$
Since $(0,1) > (1-p,0)$ in $\mathbb{Z} \times \{ 0, 1 \}$, this is the desired Postnikov tower for $ \mathcal{O}_{\mathbb{P}^1_{\mathbb{C}}}(n)$. If $n<k$, just consider the dual exact sequence and proceed similarly. Now, if $\mathcal{T}$ is a torsion sheaf of degree $d$ with a point as support, we have a short exact sequence: $$0 \longrightarrow  \mathcal{O}_{\mathbb{P}^1_{\mathbb{C}}}(k)^{\oplus d} \longrightarrow  \mathcal{O}_{\mathbb{P}^1_{\mathbb{C}}}(k+1)^{\oplus d} \longrightarrow  \mathcal{T} \longrightarrow 0$$ 
and again, rotating the induces triangle, we get $$ \mathcal{O}_{\mathbb{P}^1_{\mathbb{C}}}(k+1)^{\oplus d} \longrightarrow  \mathcal{T} \longrightarrow \mathcal{O}_{\mathbb{P}^1_{\mathbb{C}}}(k)[1]^{\oplus d} \longrightarrow  $$
which is the Postnikov tower for $\mathcal{T}$, so we are done. 
\end{proof}

Observe that for $p \in \mathbb{Z}_{\ge 1}$ the slicings $\mathscr{P}^{k,p}$, with $k \in \mathbb{Z}$, are all in the same orbit of the action of $\textnormal{Aut}(\mathscr{D})$ on $\textnormal{Slice}_{\mathbb{Z} \times \{ 0, 1 \}}(\mathscr{D})$: $\mathscr{P}^{k,p}$ is obtained from $\mathscr{P}^{0,p}$ by twisting by $\mathcal{O}_{\mathbb{P}^1_{\mathbb{C}}}(k)$. \\

\begin{prop}
For $p \in \mathbb{Z}_{\ge 1}$ and $k \in \mathbb{Z}$, $$\heartsuit_{k,p}=\langle \mathcal{O}_{\mathbb{P}^1_{\mathbb{C}}}(k)[p], \mathcal{O}_{\mathbb{P}^1_{\mathbb{C}}}(k+1) \rangle $$ 
is a heart of $\mathscr{D}$. Moreover, for $p \not = 1$, it is equivalent as an abelian category to $\textnormal{Vect}_{\mathbb{C}}^{\textnormal{fd}} \times \textnormal{Vect}_{\mathbb{C}}^{\textnormal{fd}} $, which is the category of finite-dimensional representations of the discrete quiver 
\begin{center}
\begin{tikzcd}[ampersand replacement=\&]
\bullet \& \bullet 
\end{tikzcd}
\end{center}
 while $\heartsuit_{k,1}$ is equivalent to the category of finite-dimensional representations of the $2$-Kronecker quiver 
\begin{center}
\begin{tikzcd}[ampersand replacement=\&]
\bullet \arrow[bend left=25]{r} \arrow[bend right=25]{r} \& \bullet 
\end{tikzcd}
\end{center}
In particular, $\heartsuit_{p,k}$ is of finite length for each $p \in \mathbb{Z}_{\ge 1}$, $k \in \mathbb{Z}$. 
\end{prop}

\begin{proof}
 To see that the above are hearts, just apply Proposition ??? to $\mathscr{P}^{k,p}$. NON TI SCORDAR L'EQUVALENZA.
\end{proof}


